{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.13","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":30378,"datasetId":23777,"databundleVersionId":30535,"isSourceIdPinned":false}],"dockerImageVersionId":31400,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Region-based Convolutional Neural Network\n\n**R-CNN** stands for **Region-based Convolutional Neural Network**.\nIt is a deep learning method for **object detection**, introduced by Ross Girshick and collaborators in 2014.\n\nObject detection means:\n\n1. **Finding where objects are** in an image (bounding boxes)\n2. **Classifying what those objects are**\n\nFor example, in one image the model may detect:\n\n* a dog\n* a bicycle\n* a person\n\nand **draw boxes** around each object.\n\nBefore R-CNN, image classification models could say *what* objects existed in an image, but not *where* they were located. R-CNN addressed this by first generating candidate object regions and then classifying each region.\n\nThink of R-CNN like this:\n\n1. Search image for possible objects\n2. Wrap each possible object to fixed size\n3. Ask CNN “What is this?”\n4. Keep best answers\n\n## Why R-CNN Was Important\n\nBefore R-CNN, object detection mostly used:\n\n* hand-crafted features(kernel weight defined manually)\n* sliding windows\n* traditional machine learning  \n    Before deep learning, object detection pipelines looked like this:\n    1. Extract Hand-Crafted Features\n       * Image → HOG Features\n    2. Train Classical ML Model  \n      Use algorithms like:\n       * SVM (Support Vector Machine)\n       * Decision Trees\n       * Random Forest\n       * AdaBoost\n\nR-CNN showed that **CNNs (Convolutional Neural Networks)** could dramatically improve detection accuracy. It became the foundation for later systems:\n\n* Fast R-CNN\n* Faster R-CNN\n* Mask R-CNN\n\n## Goal of R-CNN\n\nGiven an image:\n\n* Detect objects present\n* Identify object classes\n* Predict object locations using bounding boxes\n\nExample:\n\nInput image:\n\n```\nImage: Street scene\nContains:\n- Person\n- Car\n- Bicycle\n```\n\nDesired output:\n\n```\nPerson → Bounding box (x1,y1,x2,y2)\nCar → Bounding box (x1,y1,x2,y2)\nBicycle → Bounding box (x1,y1,x2,y2)\n```\n\n## R-CNN Architecture\n\n![R-CNN Architecture](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/masum184e/handbook-old/removed/images/cnn/r_cnn.png)\n\nThe process consists of several stages:\n\n1. Input image                          \n2. Region proposal generation\n    * Selective Search(~2000 region proposals)\n3. Warp regions to fixed size\n4. CNN feature extraction\n5. Classification using SVM\n6. Bounding-box regression refinement\n\n### Region Proposal Generation\n\nInstead of sliding a window across the entire image at every scale, R-CNN uses **Selective Search**.\n\nSelective Search proposes approximately:\n\n```\n~2000 candidate regions/image\n```\n\nThese regions are likely to contain objects.\n\nSuppose we have:\n\n```\nImage size: 500×500\n```\n\nSelective search may produce:\n\n```\nRegion 1: dog candidate\nRegion 2: tree candidate\nRegion 3: wheel candidate\n...\nRegion 2000\n```\n\nThe purpose is to reduce search space.\n\n#### How Selective Search works\n\nIt groups pixels according to:\n\n* color similarity\n* texture\n* size\n* shape compatibility\n\nSmall regions merge recursively.\n\nExample:\n\nInitial segmentation:\n\n```\n[grass][grass][dog]\n[grass][dog][dog]\n```\n\nRegions with similar properties merge:\n\n```\n[grass]\n[dog]\n```\n\nBounding boxes around merged regions become proposals.\n\n### Warp Candidate Regions\n\nCNN requires fixed-size input.\n\nSuppose CNN accepts:\n\n```\n227×227\n```\n\nCandidate regions differ:\n\n```\nRegion A: 50×70\nRegion B: 200×300\nRegion C: 120×150\n```\n\nAll are resized:\n\n```\n50×70 →227×227\n200×300→227×227\n120×150→227×227\n```\n\n### CNN Feature Extraction\n\nEach resized proposal passes through a CNN (originally AlexNet).It outputs feature vectors.\n\nExample:\n\n```\nProposal:\ndog image patch\n```\n\nCNN output:\n\n```\n[0.32,0.81,0.12,....,0.45]\n\n4096-dimensional feature vector\n```\n\nThis vector represents important visual patterns:\n\n* edges\n* corners\n* textures\n* shapes\n\n### Classification using SVM\n\nInstead of using CNN softmax directly, original R-CNN trains separate SVM classifiers.\n\nFor each object class:\n\n```\nDog SVM\nCat SVM\nCar SVM\nPerson SVM\n```\n\nSuppose feature vector:\n\n```\nx=[0.32,0.81,...]\n```\n\nSVM outputs:\n\n```\nDog score =0.91\nCat score =0.02\nCar score =0.10\n```\n\nPrediction:\n\n```\nDog\n```\n\n### Bounding Box Regression\n\nThe proposed box is rarely perfect.\n\nInitial proposal:\n\n```\n(x=50,y=30,w=100,h=120)\n```\n\nTrue object:\n\n```\n(x=45,y=25,w=115,h=130)\n```\n\nRegression learns corrections:\n\n```\nΔx=-5\nΔy=-5\nΔw=15\nΔh=10\n```\n\nRefined result:\n\n```\n(45,25,115,130)\n```\n\nThis improves localization accuracy.\n","metadata":{"_uuid":"8f2839f25d086af736a60e9eeb907d3b93b6e0e5","_cell_guid":"b1076dfc-b9ad-4769-8c92-a6c4dae69d19"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import kagglehub\n\npath = kagglehub.dataset_download(\"tongpython/cat-and-dog\")\n\nprint(\"Dataset downloaded to:\", path)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-05-28T09:30:44.750794Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-05-28T09:30:44.751926Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-05-28T09:30:44.831804Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-05-28T09:30:44.751871Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-05-28T09:30:44.830880Z"}},"outputs":[{"name":"stdout","text":"Dataset downloaded to: /kaggle/input/datasets/tongpython/cat-and-dog\n